'''Pedro J. Déniz Acosta''' (born 1964, Santa Brígida, [[Las Palmas de Gran Canaria]], [[Canary Islands]], Spain) is a Spanish interdisciplinary artist who has developed art projects and experiences ranging from the objectual art to [[installation art]], from [[art photography]] to [[video art]], cultivating [[art intervention]], [[performance art]], [[visual poetry]] and [[graphic design]].

==Biography==
In 1998 inaugurated the project ''La Puente'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/user/SirocoFactory#p/u/0/edEfA9x4vgY&feature=related |title=Ayoze .O´Shanahan |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date= |accessdate=2016-12-10}}</ref> which represents a turning point in his work, opening channels of communication and artistic action by launching bottles at the height of the [[zero meridian]] message wrapper made by different artists. 
In 2002 his first exhibition in the Hall of San Antonio Abad from Centro Atlántico de Arte Moderno, CAAM.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://caam.net/en/index.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-11-13 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100330033229/http://www.caam.net/en/index.htm |archivedate=2010-03-30 |df= }}</ref> That same year, presented along the Moroccan artist [[Mounir Fatmi]] the performance ''Power line - Imagen y poder''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/user/pjdeniz#p/u/11/pnjiAyonpMw&feature=related |title=Pedro Déniz |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date= |accessdate=2016-12-10}}</ref> in Espacio C Contemporary Art, Camargo, Santander.
The two artists collaborate again a year later at the Second International Contemporary Art Hybrid Spaces, Osorio, Teror, Gran Canaria with the performance ''Hybrid Spaces'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/user/pjdeniz#p/u/14/B1TiNSibBMA&feature=related |title=Pedro Déniz |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date= |accessdate=2016-12-10}}</ref> both actions intended to place the viewer at a point of reflection on the cultural frictions. As part of Performando, meeting of performances held in Las Palmas de Gran Canaria running performance ''Paper Memories''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=64h8CR8qdCU&feature=related |title=el papel de la memoria |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date=2009-02-19 |accessdate=2016-12-10}}</ref> by building a wall through fragments of the press in order to question the information that we relegate the media.
In October 2003, includes a photographic installation called ''Welcome'' in Contemporary African Photography Biennale, 5èmes [[African Photography Encounters|Rencontres Africaines de la Photographie]], Bamako, Mali. The same year, ''Dulce-sal'' exhibits a photographic installation based on migration issues included in the collective project of the Aula del Mestizaje, [[University of Las Palmas de Gran Canaria]]. The artist Ricardo Basbaum (Brazil), Robin Rhode (South Africa) and Pedro Déniz showed the group exhibition called ''3 Scenarios'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://caam.net/es/exposiciones/saa/2005/tresescenarios.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-11-13 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723034154/http://caam.net/es/exposiciones/saa/2005/tresescenarios.htm |archivedate=2011-07-23 |df= }}</ref> the installation was from March to April in the Hall of San Antonio Abad del Centro Atlántico de Arte Moderno CAAM in 2005.
One of his visual poems selected for the exhibition ''Disagreements. About art, politics and public sphere in the Spanish State'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.macba.cat/controller.php?p_action=show_page&pagina_id=34&inst_id=20039 |title=Desacuerdos |website=Macba.cat |date= |accessdate=2016-12-10}}</ref> experimental poetry section at the [[Barcelona Museum of Contemporary Art]] [[MACBA]]. That same year he presented his video ''May day''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/user/pjdeniz#p/u/8/P4dJ7jbecSg&feature=related |title=Pedro Déniz |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date= |accessdate=2016-12-10}}</ref> in the context of the 6th Biennial Photography in [[Bamako]], [[Mali]]. During the months of April and May 2006 participated in the second part of ''Violencias Urban(istic)a'' to the MAPFRE Foundation in Las Palmas de Gran Canaria and Santa Cruz de Tenerife, Canary Islands Government. That year also presented at the Biennial of Dakar his work ''Ajuy''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/user/pjdeniz#p/u/18/9LtxOE6Zf38&feature=related |title=Pedro Déniz |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date= |accessdate=2016-12-10}}</ref> within the multimedia project Meeting Point.
October to December 2007 presented in the Gallery of the [[Metropolitan Autonomous University]] (UAM) in Mexico City ''Transit, the territories of the reality'' with artists Jose Domingo Diaz and Luzardo who seek challenge his works the concept of the reality imposed by the dominant culture. In April 2008 he participated with the performance ''Jappy New Year'' in the Circo Project, an international event and Audiovisual Performance, [[Havana]], [[Cuba]].
Under the Interaction Meeting organized by [[Gran Canaria Espacio Digital]] introduces its performance ''Transit/Blindness''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/user/pjdeniz#p/u/3/NYvGk97hzOI&feature=related |title=Pedro Déniz |publisher=[[YouTube]] |date= |accessdate=2016-12-10}}</ref> where it investigates the loss of the root causes by migration. In 2009 exhibited at the 10th [[Havana Biennial]] interactive installation ''Trench of thought''<ref name="test">{{cite web |url=http://www.bienalhabana.cult.cu/bienaldelahabana/en/boletin.php?nop=12 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-11-13 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100710224420/http://www.bienalhabana.cult.cu/bienaldelahabana/en/boletin.php?nop=12 |archivedate=2010-07-10 |df= }}</ref> where Déniz reflected through his work the fragility of thought plural. In 2016 the Galerie St. Gertrude, Hamburg, realized in cooperation with the artist the first exhibition in Germany.<ref name="st-gertrude1">{{cite web|url=http://www.st-gertrude.de/de/exhibitions/pan_duro_pedro_deniz |title=Pan duro - Pedro Déniz - Ausstellungen - Galerie und Verlag St. Gertude |website=St-gertrude.de |date= |accessdate=2016-12-10}}</ref>

